{"title_page": "Kiriji War", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=April 2020}}{{lead missing|date=April 2020}}{{sections|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Kiriji War <br /><small> ({{lang|yo|Ogun K\u00edr\u00ecj\u00ed}})\n| width       = \n| partof      = \n| image       = \n| image_size  =\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 1877-1893 \n| place       = Yorubaland, now Southwestern [[Nigeria]]\n| coordinates = <!--Use the {{coord}} template -->\n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = \n| result      = Military Stalemate\n*Ekiti people gain independence on September 23, 1886\n*British-Ijebu War\n*Capture of Ilorin by Royal Nigeria Company in 1897\n*Siege of Oyo\n*Subsequent colonization and annexation of Yorubaland \n*creation of [[British Nigeria]]\n| status      = \n| combatants_header = Belligerents \n| combatant1  = Western Yoruba (Ibadan)\n| combatant2  = Eastern Yoruba (Ekiti-Parapo)\n| combatant3  = \n| commander1  = Obadoke Latoosa<br>Babalola Ajayi<br>''\n| commander2  = Fabunmi of Okemesi<br>Saraibi Ogedengbe<br>Karara of Ilorin<br>''\n| commander3  = \n| strength1   = estimated 100,000\n| strength2   = 10,000 in 1879, 100,000 at end of the war\n| casualties1 = unknown \n| casualties2 = unknown \n| casualties3 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = \n}}\nThe '''Kiriji War''', also known as the Ekiti-Parapo War, was a 16 year long civil war between the [[Yoruba|Yoruba people]], specifically divided between the Western Yoruba, which was mainly [[Ibadan]] and the Eastern Yoruba, who were the [[Ekiti people]] and the [[Ijesha]]. During the war, all the subethnic groups of the Yoruba either supported the Ibadan or the Ekiti. The main reason for the civil war was an attempt to halt the expansive efforts of the Ibadan city-state, which attempted to replace the Oyo Empire as the dominant region in Yorubaland.<ref>https://opinion.premiumtimesng.com/2017/09/27/kiriji-the-worlds-longest-civil-war-by-adewale-adeoye/</ref> In addition, Ibadan wanted a unified Yoruba nation similar to that of the [[Oyo Empire]], while the Ekiti wanted a loose confederation of cities that had existed in the Ekiti region.\n\nThe fall of the [[Oyo Empire]], which had dominated the region for 500 years left a gap in the government of Yorubaland. Many city states, which were previous provinces of the empire, rose up to replace the dominant Oyo Empire, including Ibadan. Ibadan had won the 1840 Osogbo War and the Battle of Ijaiye in 1862 and had grew in immense power, almost rising to that of its predecessor.\n\nThe Western Yoruba, the Ibadan, were led by the Aare Ona Kakanfo, Obadake Latosa, the military commander-in-chief. They quickly gained the support of people of [[Modakeke]], [[Offa]], and [[Oyo]]. The Eastern Yoruba, known as the Ekiti Parapo, were led by Fabunmi from the town of Oke-Mesi and was later led by Saraibi Ogedengbe, the Balogun (Captain) of Ijeshaland. Most of the other Yoruba groups supported the Ekiti, including the [[Ijebu]], [[Ife]], [[Egba]], [[Akoko]], [[Igbomina]], [[Ilorin]], and [[Kabba]].<ref>https://odediranodeyinka.wordpress.com/2017/02/08/ogun-kiriji-the-kiriji-war-1877-1893/</ref>\n\nThe civil war saw one of the most technically advanced and decisive wars in Western Africa, with the use of cannons and imported guns from [[Hamburg]], Germany.<ref>https://ruhm.es/index.php/RUHM/article/download/570/494</ref> Weapons were also imported through the Lagos Harbor and Benin. The Ekiti-Parapo also used several modern tactics like the building of trenches and platoons, a spy network with the headquarters in the town of [[Ilara-Mokin]], and the use of animal behavior and symbols as signals in the war.<ref>https://opinion.premiumtimesng.com/2017/09/27/kiriji-the-worlds-longest-civil-war-by-adewale-adeoye/</ref>\n\nThe war unofficially ended with the signing of a peace treaty of September 26, 1886 that granted independence to the Ekiti union. However, conflict still occurred around the Ijebu area that did not end till the conquering of the Ijebu by the British during the British-Ijebu War. Sir [[Robert Lister Bower]]\nconvinced the 2 warring sides to surrender as they had both been severely weakened during the war.<ref>https://ruhm.es/index.php/RUHM/article/download/570/494</ref> Unable to prevent the occupation of the British, Southern Nigeria was subsequently declared a protectorate of the British Empire. The casualties of the war are unknown, but it is said that there was no killing of children or women, and about 500,000 soldiers fought in the war in total.<ref>https://opinion.premiumtimesng.com/2017/09/27/kiriji-the-worlds-longest-civil-war-by-adewale-adeoye/</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name \"Kiriji\" is an onomatopoeic word that is said to describe the sound of cannons used by the Ekiti-Parapo troops, and it was the first war in the region that used these weapons.<ref>https://www.africanexponent.com/post/10324-the-worlds-longest-ethnic-civil-war-1877-1893</ref><ref>https://oldnaija.com/2019/03/18/the-kiriji-war-1877-1893/</ref> The other name, the \u00c8k\u00ect\u00ec-Parap\u1ecd\u0300 War, comes from the name given to the Eastern Yoruba forces, and means in the Yoruba language \"Ekiti Union.\"\n\n===Background===\n\n==Fall of the Oyo Empire==\n\n{{Empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Rise of the Ibadan Empire==\n\n{{Empty section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Ekiti Revolt==\n\n===Course of the War===\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=April 2020}}{{lead missing|date=April 2020}}{{sections|date=April 2020}}}}\n\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Kiriji War <br /><small> ({{lang|yo|Ogun K\u00edr\u00ecj\u00ed}})\n| width       = \n| partof      = \n| image       = \n| image_size  =\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 1877-1893 \n| place       = Yorubaland, now Southwestern [[Nigeria]]\n| coordinates = <!--Use the {{coord}} template -->\n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = \n| result      = Military Stalemate\n*Ekiti people gain independence on September 23, 1886\n*British-Ijebu War\n*Capture of Ilorin by Royal Nigeria Company in 1897\n*Siege of Oyo\n*Subsequent colonization and annexation of Yorubaland \n*creation of [[British Nigeria]]\n| status      = \n| combatants_header = Belligerents \n| combatant1  = Western Yoruba (Ibadan)\n| combatant2  = Eastern Yoruba (Ekiti-Parapo)\n| combatant3  = \n| commander1  = Obadoke Latoosa<br>Babalola Ajayi<br>''\n| commander2  = Fabunmi of Okemesi<br>Saraibi Ogedengbe<br>Karara of Ilorin<br>''\n| commander3  = \n| strength1   = estimated 100,000\n| strength2   = 10,000 in 1879, 100,000 at end of the war\n| casualties1 = unknown \n| casualties2 = unknown \n| casualties3 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = \n}}\nThe Kiriji War, also known as the Ekiti-Parapo War, was a 16 year long civil war between the [[Yoruba|Yoruba people]], specifically divided between the Western Yoruba, which was mainly [[Ibadan]] and the Eastern Yoruba, who were the [[Ekiti people]] and the [[Ijesha]]. During the war, all the subethnic groups of the Yoruba either supported the Ibadan or the Ekiti. The main reason for the civil war was an attempt to halt the expansive efforts of the Ibadan city-state, which attempted to replace the Oyo Empire as the dominant region in Yorubaland.<ref>https://opinion.premiumtimesng.com/2017/09/27/kiriji-the-worlds-longest-civil-war-by-adewale-adeoye/</ref>In addition, Ibadan wanted a unified Yoruba nation similar to that of the [[Oyo Empire]], while the Ekiti wanted a loose confederation of cities that had existed in the Ekiti region. \n\nThe fall of the [[Oyo Empire]], which had dominated the region for 500 years left a gap in the government of Yorubaland. Many city states, which were previous provinces of the empire, rose up to replace the dominant Oyo Empire, including Ibadan. Ibadan had won the 1840 Osogbo War and the Battle of Ijaiye in 1862 and had grew in immense power, almost rising to that of its predecessor.\n\nThe Western Yoruba, the Ibadan, were led by the Aare Ona Kakanfo, Obadake Latosa, the military commander-in-chief. They quickly gained the support of people of [[Modakeke]], [[Offa]], and [[Oyo]]. The Eastern Yoruba, known as the Ekiti Parapo, were led by Fabunmi from the town of Oke-Mesi and was later led by Saraibi Ogedengbe, the Balogun (Captain) of Ijeshaland. Most of the other Yoruba groups supported the Ekiti, including the [[Ijebu]], [[Ife]], [[Egba]], [[Akoko]], [[Igbomina]], [[Ilorin]], and [[Kabba]].<ref>https://odediranodeyinka.wordpress.com/2017/02/08/ogun-kiriji-the-kiriji-war-1877-1893/</ref>\n\nThe civil war saw one of the most technically advanced and decisive wars in Western Africa, with the use of cannons and imported guns from [[Hamburg]], Germany. <ref>https://ruhm.es/index.php/RUHM/article/download/570/494</ref> Weapons were also imported through the Lagos Harbor and Benin. The Ekiti-Parapo also used several modern tactics like the building of trenches and platoons, a spy network with the headquarters in the town of [[Ilara-Mokin]], and the use of animal behavior and symbols as signals in the war.<ref>https://opinion.premiumtimesng.com/2017/09/27/kiriji-the-worlds-longest-civil-war-by-adewale-adeoye/</ref>\n\nThe war unofficially ended with the signing of a peace treaty of September 26, 1886 that granted independence to the Ekiti union. However, conflict still occurred around the Ijebu area that did not end till the conquering of the Ijebu by the British during the British-Ijebu War. Sir [[Robert Lister Bower]]\nconvinced the 2 warring sides to surrender as they had both been severely weakened during the war<ref>https://ruhm.es/index.php/RUHM/article/download/570/494</ref>. Unable to prevent the occupation of the British, Southern Nigeria was subsequently declared a protectorate of the British Empire. The casualties of the war are unknown, but it is said that there was no killing of children or women, and about 500,000 soldiers fought in the war in total.<ref>https://opinion.premiumtimesng.com/2017/09/27/kiriji-the-worlds-longest-civil-war-by-adewale-adeoye/</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name \"Kiriji\" is an onomatopoeic word that is said to describe the sound of cannons used by the Ekiti-Parapo troops, and it was the first war in the region that used these weapons.<ref>https://www.africanexponent.com/post/10324-the-worlds-longest-ethnic-civil-war-1877-1893</ref><ref>https://oldnaija.com/2019/03/18/the-kiriji-war-1877-1893/</ref>. The other name, the \u00c8k\u00ect\u00ec-Parap\u1ecd\u0300 War, comes from the name given to the Eastern Yoruba forces, and means in the Yoruba language \"Ekiti Union.\"\n\n===Background===\n==Fall of the Oyo Empire==\n==Rise of the Ibadan Empire==\n==Ekiti Revolt== \n\n===Course of the War===\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, added  Empty section (2),uncategorisedtags", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kiriji_War"}
{"title_page": "Mouth Sounds", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Mouth Sounds\n| type       = mixtape\n| artist     = [[Neil Cicierega]]\n| cover      = MouthSoundsCover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{start date|2014|04|27}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Mashup (music)|Mashup]], [[remix]]<ref name=fast>{{cite news|first=Dan|last=Solomon|date=July 28, 2014|url=http://www.fastcocreate.com/3033656/behind-the-mind-melting-mouth-silence-mashup-thats-delighting-and-upsetting-the-internet|title=The Mind-Melting \"Mouth Silence\" Mashup That's Delighting and Upsetting the Internet|newspaper=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]|accessdate=November 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106183840/http://www.fastcocreate.com/3033656/behind-the-mind-melting-mouth-silence-mashup-thats-delighting-and-upsetting-the-internet|archive-date=November 6, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| length     = {{duration|m=56|s=08}}\n| label      =\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = Nature Tapes EP\n| prev_year  = 2013\n| next_title = [[Mouth Silence]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n\n'''''Mouth Sounds''''' is a [[Mashup (music)|mashup]] album by American musician [[Neil Cicierega]]. The album was released [[Independent record label|independently]] by Cicierega on April 27, 2014. Consisting of mashups pairing [[Top 40 Mainstream|Top 40]] hits of the 1980s and 1990s along with [[Smash Mouth]]'s \"[[All Star (song)|All Star]]\", ''Mouth Sounds'' received positive reviews from music critics. It received a second installment, ''[[Mouth Silence]]'', months later, which followed the same mashup format, and a third installment in ''[[Mouth Moods]]'' in 2017.\n\n==Background==\n{{Quote box\n| quote  = \"When I decided to mash up Smash Mouth with John Lennon, of course I was thinking, \u2018This is super blasphemous, this is designed to make people angry.\u2019\"\n| source = \u2014Neil Cicierega explains his thinking behind the creation of the track \"Imagine All Star People\"<ref name=fast />\n| width  = 23%\n| align  = left\n| style  = padding:10px;\n}}\nCicierega began work on the album after discovering multiple raw instrument tracks from songs featured on the [[music video game]] series ''[[Rock Band]]''.<ref name=fast /> Because ''Rock Band'' requires players to control individual instruments for each track, all artists featured in ''Rock Band'' must provide the [[Stem (audio)|stems]] of each song featured in the game. With access to these tracks, Cicierega was able to create mashups of the provided songs. The process was mostly trial and error, where he paired songs together randomly, and kept what sounded good.<ref name=fast /> Cicierega tried to only pull popular songs, explaining \"If you're doing a comedy album with mashups, then you definitely want to use songs that people will recognize.\"<ref name=fast /> The purpose of the album was to make Cicierega laugh, but also to offend fans of the songs and artists he used in the album.\n\n''Mouth Sounds''{{'}} development dates as far back as early 2013, when the song \"No Credit Card\" (a remix of [[Huey Lewis and the News]]' \"[[The Power of Love (Huey Lewis and the News song)|The Power of Love]]\") appeared on Neil Cicierega's [[SoundCloud]] account on February 6, 2013.<ref name=credit>{{cite AV media |people=[[Neil Cicierega]] |year=2013 |title=No Credit Card |medium=audio |url=https://soundcloud.com/neilcic/no-credit-card |accessdate=November 6, 2014 |format=streamed |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112110930/https://soundcloud.com/neilcic/no-credit-card |archive-date=November 12, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=neilTwit1>{{cite web |title= Tweet Number 496909166783766528 |url= https://twitter.com/neilyourself/status/496909166783766528 |first= Neil |last= Cicierega |date= 6 August 2014 |accessdate= 13 September 2015 |quote= people forget that Mouth Sounds is mostly just a compilation of joke songs I posted on tumblr over a couple year span |work= [[Twitter]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151112213236/https://twitter.com/neilyourself/status/496909166783766528 |archive-date= 12 November 2015 |url-status= live }}</ref> Over the following year, rougher edits of the songs \"Vivid Memories Turn to Fantasies,\" \"The Sharpest Tool,\" \"Modest Mouth,\" \"Imma Let It Be,\" \"Like Tears in Chocolate Rain,\" \"Melt Everyone,\" and \"Smooth Flow,\" would be uploaded to the same SoundCloud, with the final track, \"Mullet with Butterfly Wings,\" dropping just over a week before Mouth Sounds itself was released.<ref name=mullet>{{cite AV media |people=[[Neil Cicierega]] |year=2013 |title=Mullet With Butterfly Wings |medium=audio |url=https://soundcloud.com/neilcic/mullet-with-butterfly-wings |accessdate=November 6, 2014 |format=streamed |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112111054/https://soundcloud.com/neilcic/mullet-with-butterfly-wings |archive-date=November 12, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> In addition, Cicierega posted a [[Music Video]] for \"The Sharpest Tool\" (titled \"MOUTH\") to his main [[YouTube]] channel a year earlier on February 9th, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XAsPeY8BsQU|title=MOUTH|last=Cicierega|first=Neil|date=2013-02-09|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>   \n\nWhile developing the prequel to ''Mouth Sounds'', Cicierega created a setting for both albums, concerning the existence of [[multiverse|parallel universes]]. In the universe with which ''Mouth Sounds'' lies, the band Smash Mouth exists, but not in the parallel universe created for ''[[Mouth Silence]]'' (which lacks any overt Smash Mouth-related mixes). In both universes, Cicierega delineated that a \"war of music\" continues on, explaining the reasoning behind the mashups.\n\nNumerous [[Easter egg (media)|easter eggs]] have been found in the digital files for ''Mouth Sounds'' and ''Mouth Silence'' that each relate to \"All Star\". For example, when the metadata of every track on the former is viewed, the creation date of all the files is May 4, 1999 which was the release date of \"All Star.\" On the cover of the album, [[Shrek (character)|Shrek]] can be seen on the glasses of Cicierega, referencing how \"All Star\" was used at the beginning of [[Shrek]].\n\n==Reception==\n''Mouth Sounds'' received mostly positive reviews from critics. Katie Rife, writing for ''[[The A.V. Club]]'', called the mixtape \"brilliant,\" citing its ability to toy with the listener's nostalgia held towards the songs included, and wrapped up her review by suggesting the album to those that enjoy the thought of \"dropping acid at a [[Media Play]] going-out-of-business sale.\"<ref name=avclub>{{cite news|first=Katie|last=Rife|date=April 29, 2014|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/mouth-sounds-punishing-90s-nostalgia-mixtape-world-203927|title=\"Mouth Sounds\" is the punishing \u201990s nostalgia mixtape the world deserves|newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=November 5, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106092649/http://www.avclub.com/article/mouth-sounds-punishing-90s-nostalgia-mixtape-world-203927|archive-date=November 6, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Ben Simon of Music Putty also wrote of Mouth Sounds' ability to relate to the listener's childhood memories, writing, \"nostalgia is the album\u2019s unifying theme,\" and citing the third track, \"D'oh,\" as an example of when it \"is taken to its most equally incredible and horrific extreme.\"<ref name=putty>{{cite web |url=http://musicputty.wordpress.com/2014/05/05/neil-cicierega-mouth-sounds/ |title=Neil Cicierega \u2013 Mouth Sounds |last1=Simon |first1=Ben |date=May 5, 2014 |website=Music Putty |accessdate=November 5, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220183142/http://musicputty.wordpress.com/2014/05/05/neil-cicierega-mouth-sounds/ |archive-date=December 20, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of January 11, 2019, the mixtape has received over 940,000 plays on SoundCloud.<ref name=\"msCloud\">{{cite AV media|url=https://soundcloud.com/neilcic/mouth-sounds|title=Mouth Sounds|date=|people=[[Neil Cicierega]]|first=|type=|language=|year=2014|accessdate=January 11, 2019|format=streamed|medium=audio|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105032135/https://soundcloud.com/neilcic/mouth-sounds|archive-date=January 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = \n| extra_column = Featured works\n| title1 = Promenade (Satellite Pictures at an Exhibition)\n| length1 = 1:25\n| extra1 = {{blist| Smash Mouth's \"All Star\"| [[Modest Mussorgsky]]'s \"[[Promenade (Pictures at an Exhibition)]]\"}}\n| title2 = Modest Mouth\n| length2 = 3:47\n| extra2 = {{blist| Smash Mouth's \"All Star\"| [[Modest Mouse]]'s \"[[Float On (Modest Mouse song)|Float On]]\"| [[Lupe Fiasco]]'s \"[[The Show Goes On (song)|The Show Goes On]]\"}}\n| title3 = D'oh\n| length3 = 1:54\n| extra3 = {{blist| [[Austin Powers (character)|Austin Powers]]' \"Yeah baby!\"| [[Homer Simpson]]'s \"[[D'oh!]]\"| [[Fred Newman (actor)|Fred Newman]]'s ''[[Doug (TV series)|Doug]]'' theme song| [[The Dave Matthews Band|Dave Matthews Band's]] \"[[Ants Marching]]\"| [[Sir Mix-a-Lot]]'s \"[[Baby Got Back]]\"| [[Talking Heads]]' \"[[Once in a Lifetime (Talking Heads song)|Once in a Lifetime]]\"}}\n| title4 = Vivid Memories Turn to Fantasies\n| length4 = 2:44\n| extra4 = {{blist| [[Will Smith]]'s \"[[Men in Black (song)|Men in Black]]\"}}\n| title5 = Bills Like Jean Spirit\n| length5 = 4:45\n| extra5 = {{blist| [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s \"[[Smells Like Teen Spirit]]\"| [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Billie Jean]]\"}}\n| title6 = Full Mouth\n| length6 = 2:17\n| extra6 = {{blist| Nirvana's \"Smells Like Teen Spirit\" (Continuing from the last track)|[[Jesse Frederick]]'s \"[[Everywhere You Look]]\"| Smash Mouth's \"All Star\"}}\n