r'', 1990, (self published), 774 pp, {{ISBN|0-906440-51-3}}, {{ISBN|0-906440-50-5}}\n*''Burns: A Biography of Robert Burns'', 1992, Mainstream Publishing, 672 pp, {{ISBN|1-85158-462-5}}\n*''Robert Burns, the Complete Poetical Works'', 1993, Alloway Publishing Ltd, 640 pp, {{ISBN|0-907526-62-4}}\n*''Burns, A Biography'', 2004, Alloway Publishing Ltd, 749 pp, {{ISBN|0-907526-86-1}}\n\n===Other subjects===\n*''Antiques of the future; a guide for collectors and investors'', 1970, Universe Books, 208 pp, {{ISBN|0-87663-117-0}}\n*''Glass Paperweights'', Littlehampton Book Services Ltd, 1973, 136 pp, {{ISBN|0-7063-1102-7}}\n*''The Animaliers: A Collector's Guide to the Animal Sculptors of the 19th & 20th Centuries'', Dutton, 1973, 160 pp, {{ISBN|0-525-05498-7}}\n*''Dictionary of Western Sculptors in Bronze'', 1973, Antique Collector's Club, 1977, 414 pp, {{ISBN|0-902028-55-3}}\n*''Coins: Facts and Feats'', 1993, Spink & Son Ltd, 276 pp, {{ISBN|1-85264-069-3}}\n*''Clans and Tartans of Scotland'', 2000, {{ISBN|0-517-16240-7}}\n*''Glasgow's Other River : Exploring the Kelvin'', 2000, Fort Publishing Ltd, 240 pp, published under pseudonym Alex Matheson, {{ISBN|0-9536576-2-0}}\n*''Soldiering on St Kilda'', 2002, Token Publishing Ltd, 180 pp, {{ISBN|1-870192-48-6}}\n*''The St Kilda Steamers'', 2006, The History Press Ltd, 192 pp, {{ISBN|0-7524-3878-6}}\n\n==References and sources==\n'''Notes'''\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n'''Sources'''\n*John Holman, ''Obituary: James Alexander Mackay: Philatelic writer without equal'', Gibbons Stamp Monthly, October 2007, p.&nbsp;16.\n\n==External links==\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071108033541/http://www.stampmart.co.uk/news/dedications.asp |date=8 November 2007 |title=Dedications flood in for prolific philatelist }} ''Stamp & Coin Mart''\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mackay, James A}}\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:2007 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Inverness]]\n[[Category:British philatelists]]\n[[Category:Scottish writers]]\n[[Category:Scottish historians]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:People associated with the British Museum]]\n[[Category:Scottish biographers]]\n[[Category:People convicted of theft]]\n[[Category:People involved in plagiarism controversies]]\n[[Category:20th-century British writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British historians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British historians]]\n[[Category:Philatelic authors]]\n[[Category:Self-published authors]]\n[[Category:20th-century biographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century biographers]]\n", "name_user": "Ww2censor", "label": "safe", "comment": "this is fine, I just swopped the links around", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_A._Mackay"}
{"title_page": "Jonathan Blow", "text_new": "{{short description|American game designer (Braid, The Witness) and programmer (Jai language)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Jonathan Blow\n|image=Jonathan Blow Game Access Conf '19.jpg\n|caption=Blow in 2019\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1971|11|3}}\n|birth_place=San Francisco\n|nationality = American\n|height=183 cm\n|alma_mater={{nowrap|[[University of California, Berkeley]]}}\n|occupation=Game Designer<br>Programmer\n|website=http://number-none.com/blow\n|organization=Thekla, Inc.\n|known_for=''Braid'', ''The Witness'', Jai Language\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Blow''' (born {{Birth date|1971|11|3}})<ref name = born>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/is-braid-pretentious-creator-jonathan-blow-answers-his-critics/ |title=Is Braid pretentious? Creator Jonathan Blow answers his critics |website=GamesRadar |date=2011-08-09 |access-date=2014-06-18}}</ref> is an American [[video game designer]] and [[game programmer|programmer]], who is best known as the creator of the [[independent video game]]s ''[[Braid (video game)|Braid]]'' (2008) and ''[[The Witness (2016 video game)|The Witness]]'' (2016), both of which were released to critical acclaim.\n\nFrom 2001 to 2004, Blow wrote the Inner Product column for ''[[Game Developer Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://number-none.com/product/|title=The Inner Product - Home|website=number-none.com|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref> He was the primary host of the Experimental Gameplay Workshop each March at the [[Game Developers Conference]], which has become a premier showcase for new ideas in video games.  In addition, Blow was a regular participant in the [[Indie Game Jam]]. Blow is also a founding partner of the [[Indie Fund]], an [[angel investor]] fund for independent game projects.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBlow was born in 1971. His mother was a devout ex-nun who constantly reminded her scientifically inclined young son about the imminent return of Jesus. (When Blow's older sister came out as a lesbian in the mid-1980s, their mother disowned her.) Blow's father worked all day for the defense contractor TRW, then came home and spent every possible moment alone in his den, where the children were not welcome. Blow would say in an interview with ''[[The Atlantic]]'', \"Early on, I detected that there weren't good examples at home, so I kind of had to figure things out on my own ... I had to adopt a paradigm of self-sufficiency.\"<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2012/05/the-most-dangerous-gamer/308928/|title=The Most Dangerous Gamer|accessdate=2018-01-19|date=May 2012|work=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\nBlow grew up in Rancho Pe\u00f1asquitos, San Diego, and went to Mt. Carmel High School. He then studied [[computer science]] and [[creative writing]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] and was president of the [[Computer Science Undergraduate Association]] for a semester. He left the university in 1994, a semester before he would have graduated.<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/><ref>[http://konzole.hrej.cz/clanky/tema/jonathan-blow-california-dreamin/ Jonathan Blow: California Dreamin'], Hrej.cz (Czech)</ref><ref name=\"arstech thewitness\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/09/the-man-and-the-island-wandering-through-jonathan-blows-the-witness/|title=The man and the island: Wandering through Jonathan Blow's The Witness|first=Sam|last=Machkovech|date=2015-09-17|accessdate=2018-01-19|website=[[Ars Technica]]}}</ref>\n\nHe worked in San Francisco in contracting jobs, including one with [[Silicon Graphics]] to port ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' to a set-top device, until forming the game design company Bolt-Action Software with Bernt Habermeier in 1996.<ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/jonathan-blow/3040-89596/|title=Jonathan Blow (Person)|website=[[Giant Bomb]]|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> Their initial game project was to be a hovertank-based combat game called ''Wulfram'', but at the time, the video game industry was undergoing a transformation of focusing heavily on three-dimensional graphics, making it difficult for them to complete the project;{{clarify|date=June 2016|reason=It's never stated that Wulfram is not 3D.}} the team was forced to take some online database work to cover their expenditures. Subsequently, in the wake of the crash of [[dot-com bubble]], they opted to fold the business after four years in 2000, with them $100,000 in debt.<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/><ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/>\n\nFollowing Bolt-Action, Blow continued to perform contract work for companies like [[Ion Storm]], and writing for industry publications such as ''[[Game Developer Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/> He also worked on a project with [[IBM]] to create a technology demo similar to the ''Wulfram'' idea that would highlight the features of the [[Cell (microprocessor)|Cell processor]] that IBM was collaborating on, which would become a part of the [[PlayStation 3]]. Blow attempted to get additional funding to turn the demo into a full game from both [[Sony Computer Entertainment|Sony]] and [[Electronic Arts]] but was unsuccessful.<ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===''Braid''===\n{{Main|Braid (video game)}}\nIn December 2004, feeling inspired during a trip in Thailand, Blow made a prototype for a time manipulation puzzle platformer game. The demo had crude graphics, but featured the ability of the player to rewind all the objects on screen backwards in time to a previous state. Encouraged by feedback from his peers, Blow worked on the game from about April 2005 to about December that year before having the final prototype of his game, titled ''[[Braid (video game)|Braid]]''. This version won the [[Independent Games Festival]] Game Design Award at the 2006 [[Game Developers Conference]].\n\nHe continued work on the game mostly focusing on art and music while polishing some of the design until its release in 2008 on [[Xbox Live Arcade]]. By then, Blow was $40,000 in debt<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/> and had invested $200,000 into the game's development.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gibson|first=Ellie|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/gdc-braid-cost-200k-to-make-says-blow|title=GDC: Braid cost 200k to make, says Blow|website=Eurogamer|date=2009-03-25|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nThe game was released on August 8, 2008, to critical acclaim and achieved financial success, receiving an aggregate score of 93% on [[Metacritic]], making it the top-rated Xbox Live Arcade game. ''Braid'' was purchased by more than 55,000 people during the first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://braid-game.com/news/2008/08/stats-the-first-week-of-braid/|title=Braid \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb Stats: The First Week of Braid|website=Braid-game.com|date=2008-08-13|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> Blow recalled that he did not receive any money until one day he saw a lot of zeroes in his bank account.<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/>\n\n===''The Witness''===\n{{Main|The Witness (2016 video game)}}\nAnnounced in August 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.pc.gamespy.com/pc/the-witness/1010683p1.html|title=GameSpy: Johnathan Blow Announces New Game \u2013 Page 1|last=Barber|first=Tyler|website=[[GameSpy]]|date=2009-08-04|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> ''The Witness'' is a 3D first person [[puzzle game]] in which a player is stranded on an island, trying to solve various maze puzzles. Like ''Braid'' before it, Blow invested his own money\u2014reportedly $2\u20133&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kuchera|first=Ben|url=http://penny-arcade.com/report/editorial-article/jonathan-is-betting-2.5-million-youll-like-the-witness-as-much-as-braid|title=The PA Report \u2013 Jonathan Blow is betting $2.5 million you'll like The Witness as much as Braid|website=Penny-arcade.com|date=2012-03-14|accessdate=2018-01-19|via=[[archive.is]]|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130131031907/http://penny-arcade.com/report/editorial-article/jonathan-is-betting-2.5-million-youll-like-the-witness-as-much-as-braid|archivedate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nEarly public reaction to preview footage resulted in underwhelming assumptions that the game would simply be \"solving simple maze puzzles.\" Blow responded by saying that footage does not capture the problem solving process that goes on in the player's mind like in his previous game ''Braid'', and that he \"wouldn't make a game about solving a series of rote puzzles.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-witness.net/news/2010/10/about-the-blue-mazes/|title=About the Blue Mazes|date=2010-10-19|accessdate=2018-01-19|author=Blow, Jonathan}}</ref>\n\nIn previews of ''The Witness'' (often at noisy conventions), Blow had journalists play the game by themselves in a quiet environment so as to fit the tone of the game's design. There was praise of the game's previews,<ref>{{cite web|last=Rubens|first=Alex|url=http://www.g4tv.com/games/xbox-360/65972/the-witness/articles/76862/the-witness-preview-how-to-unbraid-modern-game-design|title=The Witness for Xbox 360 \u2013 Preview \u2013 The Witness Preview \u2013 How to Unbraid Modern Game Design|website=G4tv.com|date=2012-03-15|accessdate=2014-06-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103170954/http://www.g4tv.com/games/xbox-360/65972/the-witness/articles/76862/the-witness-preview-how-to-unbraid-modern-game-design|archivedate=2014-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/gdc-witnessing-jonathan-blow-s-the-witness-223458.phtml|title=GDC: Witnessing Jonathan Blow's The Witness|website=[[Destructoid]]|date=2012-03-08|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> notably Kirk Hamilton from [[Kotaku]] calling it \"an exercise in Symphonic Game Design.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamilton|first=Hamilton |url=http://kotaku.com/5893336/jonathan-blows-the-witness-is-an-exercise-in-symphonic-game-design|title=Jonathan Blow's The Witness is an Exercise in Symphonic Game Design|website=Kotaku|date=2012-03-15|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nBlow reinvested all of his remaining profit from ''Braid'' into ''The Witness,'' and had to borrow funds when his own ran out.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/the-prickly-genius-of-jonathan-blow|title=The Prickly Genius of Jonathan Blow|last=Parkin|first=Simon|date=2016-01-29|newspaper=The New Yorker|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\n===JAI language===\nIn September 2014, Blow began work on a new [[programming language]] called \"JAI\" based on ideas he had previously expressed about [[video game development]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wawro|first=Alex|title=Video: Jon Blow on building a new programming language, called Jai, for games|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/226070/Video_Jon_Blow_on_building_a_new_programming_language_for_games.php|website=Gamasutra|publisher=UBM Tech|accessdate=2018-01-19|date=2014-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Blow|first=Jonathan|title=Demo: Base language, compile-time execution|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTqZNujQOlA|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2018-01-19|date=2014-10-31}}</ref>  It is aimed at \"low-friction\" and fluid development, whilst directly supporting [[data-oriented design]] for high performance.  The language is currently active, but is a work-in-progress, as no JAI compiler has been publicly released yet. A small demo of the language was shown at Reboot Develop 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=gWv_vUgbmug|title=Jonathan Blow \"Making Game Programming Less Terrible\" Talk at Reboot Develop 2017|last=Bross|first=Daniel|website=YouTube|date=2017-04-20|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> Blow also uses [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] to regularly stream demonstrations of new language features as well as improvements to the game engine that will be bundled with the language.<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLmV5I2fxaiCKfxMBrNsU1kgKJXD3PkyxO|title=A Programming Language for Games - YouTube|website=YouTube|accessdate=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\n===''Game 3''===\nBlow's next project, tentatively titled ''Game 3'', will be broken into different installments and elaborations on the same game over the course of 20 years, making it bigger and bigger and more complex. They will be individual playable games, each related thematically and deepening in investigation of subject matter for each chapter. Blow stated that the game would not be puzzle related, that it\u2019s a very exciting project and that if \"he's gonna work on it that long, he wants it to be in the new language because he wants to enjoy working on it. This game is sort of building up the engine, and then, he\u2019ll take that new engine and use it on that 20-year game.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5xgeZ16HpH0|title=PRACTICE 2014: Jonathan Blow|website=YouTube|url-status=live|accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/07/02/jonathan-blow-how-thekla-is-moving-beyond-the-witness/|title=Jonathan Blow: How Thekla is moving beyond The Witness|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nIn March 2010, Blow, along with several independent game developers including Ron Carmel and [[Kellee Santiago]], became a founding member of the [[Indie Fund]], an [[angel investor]] fund for independent game projects.\n\nIn 2012, Blow was one of the subjects of the independent documentary film, ''[[Indie Game: The Movie]]'', where he discussed his views on the role of independent video games and his work on ''Braid''.\n\n==Philosophy and views==\nBlow has spoken many times about his views on independent video games both in interviews and in public speeches, although he has said on his blog<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the-witness.net/news/2012/05/the-depth-jam/|title=The Depth Jam|website=The-witness.net|date=2012-05-29|quote=After about eight years, though, [being a conference presenter] ran its course and I had gotten the bulk of what I was going to get from this arrangement.|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> that he has gotten what he wanted out of conferences from speaking at them. For his sometimes controversial views, he has received praise, notably being called \"the kind of righteous rebel video games need\"<ref name=\"kotaku.com\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5829591/jonathan-blow-opinionated-creator-of-two-video-games-is-attempting-to-be-profound|title=Jonathan Blow, Opinionated Creator of Two Video Games, is 'Attempting to be Profound'|last=Totilo|first=Stephen|website=Kotaku|date=2011-08-10|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> and \"a spiritual seeker, questing after truth in an as-yet-uncharted realm.\"<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/>\n\nBlow often speaks of the potential for games to be more. He has said that he tries to make games that are more adult for people with longer attention spans<ref name=\"kotaku.com\"/> and noted that games could have a \"much bigger role\" in culture in the future, but current game development does not address this potential, instead aiming for low-risk, high-profit titles.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Jonathan Blow on future of video game industry|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7417988n|series=CBS This Morning|serieslink=CBS This Morning|date= 2012-08-13|accessdate=2018-01-19|publisher=[[CBS]]}}</ref> Additionally, formerly being a physics major, Blow has expressed that games could examine the universe in similar ways that a physicist could.<ref>{{youtube|id=OGSeLSmOALU|title=IndieCade 2011: Jonathan Blow & Marc Ten Bosch}}</ref>\n\nIn referring to the progression of development in his games, Blow stated at the [[PlayStation Experience]] that he prefers to, \"keep them playable and just make them better.\" This was stated during the live-cast panel while overseeing Justin Massongill on the playable demo.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davidson|first1=Joey|title=Hands-on with The Witness on PS4|url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2013/10/25/hands-on-with-the-witness-on-ps4/|website=PlayStation.Blog|date=2013-10-25|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nBlow has spoken out against some games for immoral game design. On ''[[World of Warcraft]]'', he has said it causes societal problems by creating a false image of the meaning of life, calling it \"unethical.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=16392#.UG3cUk3A-xU|title=MIGS 2007: Jonathan Blow On The 'WoW Drug', Meaningful Games|website=Gamasutra|date=2007-11-28|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> On ''[[Farmville]]'', he has said that the design of the game reveals the developers' goal to degrade the quality of players' lives, ultimately calling it \"inherently evil.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/previews/jonathan-blow-interview-social-game-designers-goal-is-to-degrade-the-players-quality-of-life/|last=Caldwell|first=Brandon|title=Jonathan Blow interview: Do you believe social games are evil? \"Yes. Absolutely.\"|website=PC Gamer|date=2011-02-15|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nDespite ''Braid''{{'}}s success on the platform, Blow has claimed that [[Microsoft]]'s Xbox Live Arcade certification process would turn away developers because \"they kind of make themselves a pain in the ass\" and that they would lose [[market share]] to [[Steam (software)|Steam]] as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/126427/Interview_Jonathan_Blow__Xbox_Live_Arcade_A_Pain_In_The_Ass_For_Indies.php|title=Interview: Jonathan Blow \u2013 Xbox Live Arcade 'A Pain In The Ass' For Indies|website=Gamasutra|date=2011-08-11|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jonathan Blow}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TH9VCN6UkyQ&list=PLmV5I2fxaiCKfxMBrNsU1kgKJXD3PkyxO A Programming Language For Games]\n*[http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=19748/ Gamasutra interview with Jonathan Blow]\n\n{{Indie Game: The Movie}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blow, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:Video game writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:American video game programmers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American game designer (Braid, The Witness) and programmer (Jai language)}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name=Jonathan Blow\n|image=Jonathan Blow Game Access Conf '19.jpg\n|caption=Blow in 2019\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1971|11|3}}\n|birth_place=San Francisco\n|nationality = American\n|height=183 cm\n|alma_mater={{nowrap|[[University of California, Berkeley]]}}\n|occupation=Game Designer<br>Programmer\n|website=http://number-none.com/blow\n|organization=Thekla, Inc.\n|known_for=''Braid'', ''The Witness'', Jai Language\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Blow''' (born {{Birth date|1971|11|3}})<ref name = born>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/is-braid-pretentious-creator-jonathan-blow-answers-his-critics/ |title=Is Braid pretentious? Creator Jonathan Blow answers his critics |website=GamesRadar |date=2011-08-09 |access-date=2014-06-18}}</ref> is an American [[video game designer]] and [[game programmer|programmer]], who is best known as the creator of the [[independent video game]]s ''[[Braid (video game)|Braid]]'' (2008) and ''[[The Witness (2016 video game)|The Witness]]'' (2016), both of which were released to critical acclaim.\n\nFrom 2001 to 2004, Blow wrote the Inner Product column for ''[[Game Developer Magazine]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://number-none.com/product/|title=The Inner Product - Home|website=number-none.com|access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref> He was the primary host of the Experimental Gameplay Workshop each March at the [[Game Developers Conference]], which has become a premier showcase for new ideas in video games.  In addition, Blow was a regular participant in the [[Indie Game Jam]]. Blow is also a founding partner of the [[Indie Fund]], an [[angel investor]] fund for independent game projects.\n\n==Early life and education==\nBlow was born in 1971. His mother was a devout ex-nun who constantly reminded her scientifically inclined young son about the imminent return of Jesus. (When Blow's older sister came out as a lesbian in the mid-1980s, their mother disowned her.) Blow's father worked all day for the defense contractor TRW, then came home and spent every possible moment alone in his den, where the children were not welcome. Blow would say in an interview with ''[[The Atlantic]]'', \"Early on, I detected that there weren't good examples at home, so I kind of had to figure things out on my own ... I had to adopt a paradigm of self-sufficiency.\"<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2012/05/the-most-dangerous-gamer/308928/|title=The Most Dangerous Gamer|accessdate=2018-01-19|date=May 2012|work=The Atlantic}}</ref>\n\nBlow studied [[computer science]] and [[creative writing]] at the [[University of California, Berkeley]] and was president of the [[Computer Science Undergraduate Association]] for a semester. He left the university in 1994, a semester before he would have graduated.<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/><ref>[http://konzole.hrej.cz/clanky/tema/jonathan-blow-california-dreamin/ Jonathan Blow: California Dreamin'], Hrej.cz (Czech)</ref><ref name=\"arstech thewitness\">{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2015/09/the-man-and-the-island-wandering-through-jonathan-blows-the-witness/|title=The man and the island: Wandering through Jonathan Blow's The Witness|first=Sam|last=Machkovech|date=2015-09-17|accessdate=2018-01-19|website=[[Ars Technica]]}}</ref>\n\nHe worked in San Francisco in contracting jobs, including one with [[Silicon Graphics]] to port ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' to a set-top device, until forming the game design company Bolt-Action Software with Bernt Habermeier in 1996.<ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.giantbomb.com/jonathan-blow/3040-89596/|title=Jonathan Blow (Person)|website=[[Giant Bomb]]|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> Their initial game project was to be a hovertank-based combat game called ''Wulfram'', but at the time, the video game industry was undergoing a transformation of focusing heavily on three-dimensional graphics, making it difficult for them to complete the project;{{clarify|date=June 2016|reason=It's never stated that Wulfram is not 3D.}} the team was forced to take some online database work to cover their expenditures. Subsequently, in the wake of the crash of [[dot-com bubble]], they opted to fold the business after four years in 2000, with them $100,000 in debt.<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/><ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/>\n\nFollowing Bolt-Action, Blow continued to perform contract work for companies like [[Ion Storm]], and writing for industry publications such as ''[[Game Developer Magazine]]''.<ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/> He also worked on a project with [[IBM]] to create a technology demo similar to the ''Wulfram'' idea that would highlight the features of the [[Cell (microprocessor)|Cell processor]] that IBM was collaborating on, which would become a part of the [[PlayStation 3]]. Blow attempted to get additional funding to turn the demo into a full game from both [[Sony Computer Entertainment|Sony]] and [[Electronic Arts]] but was unsuccessful.<ref name=\"arstech thewitness\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===''Braid''===\n{{Main|Braid (video game)}}\nIn December 2004, feeling inspired during a trip in Thailand, Blow made a prototype for a time manipulation puzzle platformer game. The demo had crude graphics, but featured the ability of the player to rewind all the objects on screen backwards in time to a previous state. Encouraged by feedback from his peers, Blow worked on the game from about April 2005 to about December that year before having the final prototype of his game, titled ''[[Braid (video game)|Braid]]''. This version won the [[Independent Games Festival]] Game Design Award at the 2006 [[Game Developers Conference]].\n\nHe continued work on the game mostly focusing on art and music while polishing some of the design until its release in 2008 on [[Xbox Live Arcade]]. By then, Blow was $40,000 in debt<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/> and had invested $200,000 into the game's development.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gibson|first=Ellie|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/gdc-braid-cost-200k-to-make-says-blow|title=GDC: Braid cost 200k to make, says Blow|website=Eurogamer|date=2009-03-25|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nThe game was released on August 8, 2008, to critical acclaim and achieved financial success, receiving an aggregate score of 93% on [[Metacritic]], making it the top-rated Xbox Live Arcade game. ''Braid'' was purchased by more than 55,000 people during the first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://braid-game.com/news/2008/08/stats-the-first-week-of-braid/|title=Braid \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb Stats: The First Week of Braid|website=Braid-game.com|date=2008-08-13|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> Blow recalled that he did not receive any money until one day he saw a lot of zeroes in his bank account.<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/>\n\n===''The Witness''===\n{{Main|The Witness (2016 video game)}}\nAnnounced in August 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.pc.gamespy.com/pc/the-witness/1010683p1.html|title=GameSpy: Johnathan Blow Announces New Game \u2013 Page 1|last=Barber|first=Tyler|website=[[GameSpy]]|date=2009-08-04|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> ''The Witness'' is a 3D first person [[puzzle game]] in which a player is stranded on an island, trying to solve various maze puzzles. Like ''Braid'' before it, Blow invested his own money\u2014reportedly $2\u20133&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kuchera|first=Ben|url=http://penny-arcade.com/report/editorial-article/jonathan-is-betting-2.5-million-youll-like-the-witness-as-much-as-braid|title=The PA Report \u2013 Jonathan Blow is betting $2.5 million you'll like The Witness as much as Braid|website=Penny-arcade.com|date=2012-03-14|accessdate=2018-01-19|via=[[archive.is]]|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130131031907/http://penny-arcade.com/report/editorial-article/jonathan-is-betting-2.5-million-youll-like-the-witness-as-much-as-braid|archivedate=2013-01-31}}</ref>\n\nEarly public reaction to preview footage resulted in underwhelming assumptions that the game would simply be \"solving simple maze puzzles.\" Blow responded by saying that footage does not capture the problem solving process that goes on in the player's mind like in his previous game ''Braid'', and that he \"wouldn't make a game about solving a series of rote puzzles.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the-witness.net/news/2010/10/about-the-blue-mazes/|title=About the Blue Mazes|date=2010-10-19|accessdate=2018-01-19|author=Blow, Jonathan}}</ref>\n\nIn previews of ''The Witness'' (often at noisy conventions), Blow had journalists play the game by themselves in a quiet environment so as to fit the tone of the game's design. There was praise of the game's previews,<ref>{{cite web|last=Rubens|first=Alex|url=http://www.g4tv.com/games/xbox-360/65972/the-witness/articles/76862/the-witness-preview-how-to-unbraid-modern-game-design|title=The Witness for Xbox 360 \u2013 Preview \u2013 The Witness Preview \u2013 How to Unbraid Modern Game Design|website=G4tv.com|date=2012-03-15|accessdate=2014-06-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141103170954/http://www.g4tv.com/games/xbox-360/65972/the-witness/articles/76862/the-witness-preview-how-to-unbraid-modern-game-design|archivedate=2014-11-03|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/gdc-witnessing-jonathan-blow-s-the-witness-223458.phtml|title=GDC: Witnessing Jonathan Blow's The Witness|website=[[Destructoid]]|date=2012-03-08|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> notably Kirk Hamilton from [[Kotaku]] calling it \"an exercise in Symphonic Game Design.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Hamilton|first=Hamilton |url=http://kotaku.com/5893336/jonathan-blows-the-witness-is-an-exercise-in-symphonic-game-design|title=Jonathan Blow's The Witness is an Exercise in Symphonic Game Design|website=Kotaku|date=2012-03-15|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nBlow reinvested all of his remaining profit from ''Braid'' into ''The Witness,'' and had to borrow funds when his own ran out.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/the-prickly-genius-of-jonathan-blow|title=The Prickly Genius of Jonathan Blow|last=Parkin|first=Simon|date=2016-01-29|newspaper=The New Yorker|issn=0028-792X}}</ref>\n\n===JAI language===\nIn September 2014, Blow began work on a new [[programming language]] called \"JAI\" based on ideas he had previously expressed about [[video game development]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wawro|first=Alex|title=Video: Jon Blow on building a new programming language, called Jai, for games|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/226070/Video_Jon_Blow_on_building_a_new_programming_language_for_games.php|website=Gamasutra|publisher=UBM Tech|accessdate=2018-01-19|date=2014-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Blow|first=Jonathan|title=Demo: Base language, compile-time execution|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=UTqZNujQOlA|website=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=2018-01-19|date=2014-10-31}}</ref>  It is aimed at \"low-friction\" and fluid development, whilst directly supporting [[data-oriented design]] for high performance.  The language is currently active, but is a work-in-progress, as no JAI compiler has been publicly released yet. A small demo of the language was shown at Reboot Develop 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/watch?v=gWv_vUgbmug|title=Jonathan Blow \"Making Game Programming Less Terrible\" Talk at Reboot Develop 2017|last=Bross|first=Daniel|website=YouTube|date=2017-04-20|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> Blow also uses [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]] to regularly stream demonstrations of new language features as well as improvements to the game engine that will be bundled with the language.<ref>{{cite web|url=//www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLmV5I2fxaiCKfxMBrNsU1kgKJXD3PkyxO|title=A Programming Language for Games - YouTube|website=YouTube|accessdate=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\n===''Game 3''===\nBlow's next project, tentatively titled ''Game 3'', will be broken into different installments and elaborations on the same game over the course of 20 years, making it bigger and bigger and more complex. They will be individual playable games, each related thematically and deepening in investigation of subject matter for each chapter. Blow stated that the game would not be puzzle related, that it\u2019s a very exciting project and that if \"he's gonna work on it that long, he wants it to be in the new language because he wants to enjoy working on it. This game is sort of building up the engine, and then, he\u2019ll take that new engine and use it on that 20-year game.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5xgeZ16HpH0|title=PRACTICE 2014: Jonathan Blow|website=YouTube|url-status=live|accessdate=2019-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/07/02/jonathan-blow-how-thekla-is-moving-beyond-the-witness/|title=Jonathan Blow: How Thekla is moving beyond The Witness|website=VentureBeat|accessdate=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nIn March 2010, Blow, along with several independent game developers including Ron Carmel and [[Kellee Santiago]], became a founding member of the [[Indie Fund]], an [[angel investor]] fund for independent game projects.\n\nIn 2012, Blow was one of the subjects of the independent documentary film, ''[[Indie Game: The Movie]]'', where he discussed his views on the role of independent video games and his work on ''Braid''.\n\n==Philosophy and views==\nBlow has spoken many times about his views on independent video games both in interviews and in public speeches, although he has said on his blog<ref>{{cite news|url=http://the-witness.net/news/2012/05/the-depth-jam/|title=The Depth Jam|website=The-witness.net|date=2012-05-29|quote=After about eight years, though, [being a conference presenter] ran its course and I had gotten the bulk of what I was going to get from this arrangement.|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> that he has gotten what he wanted out of conferences from speaking at them. For his sometimes controversial views, he has received praise, notably being called \"the kind of righteous rebel video games need\"<ref name=\"kotaku.com\">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/5829591/jonathan-blow-opinionated-creator-of-two-video-games-is-attempting-to-be-profound|title=Jonathan Blow, Opinionated Creator of Two Video Games, is 'Attempting to be Profound'|last=Totilo|first=Stephen|website=Kotaku|date=2011-08-10|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> and \"a spiritual seeker, questing after truth in an as-yet-uncharted realm.\"<ref name=\"The Most Dangerous Gamer\"/>\n\nBlow often speaks of the potential for games to be more. He has said that he tries to make games that are more adult for people with longer attention spans<ref name=\"kotaku.com\"/> and noted that games could have a \"much bigger role\" in culture in the future, but current game development does not address this potential, instead aiming for low-risk, high-profit titles.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Jonathan Blow on future of video game industry|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=7417988n|series=CBS This Morning|serieslink=CBS This Morning|date= 2012-08-13|accessdate=2018-01-19|publisher=[[CBS]]}}</ref> Additionally, formerly being a physics major, Blow has expressed that games could examine the universe in similar ways that a physicist could.<ref>{{youtube|id=OGSeLSmOALU|title=IndieCade 2011: Jonathan Blow & Marc Ten Bosch}}</ref>\n\nIn referring to the progression of development in his games, Blow stated at the [[PlayStation Experience]] that he prefers to, \"keep them playable and just make them better.\" This was stated during the live-cast panel while overseeing Justin Massongill on the playable demo.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Davidson|first1=Joey|title=Hands-on with The Witness on PS4|url=http://blog.us.playstation.com/2013/10/25/hands-on-with-the-witness-on-ps4/|website=PlayStation.Blog|date=2013-10-25|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nBlow has spoken out against some games for immoral game design. On ''[[World of Warcraft]]'', he has said it causes societal problems by creating a false image of the meaning of life, calling it \"unethical.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=16392#.UG3cUk3A-xU|title=MIGS 2007: Jonathan Blow On The 'WoW Drug', Meaningful Games|website=Gamasutra|date=2007-11-28|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref> On ''[[Farmville]]'', he has said that the design of the game reveals the developers' goal to degrade the quality of players' lives, ultimately calling it \"inherently evil.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/previews/jonathan-blow-interview-social-game-designers-goal-is-to-degrade-the-players-quality-of-life/|last=Caldwell|first=Brandon|title=Jonathan Blow interview: Do you believe social games are evil? \"Yes. Absolutely.\"|website=PC Gamer|date=2011-02-15|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\nDespite ''Braid''{{'}}s success on the platform, Blow has claimed that [[Microsoft]]'s Xbox Live Arcade certification process would turn away developers because \"they kind of make themselves a pain in the ass\" and that they would lose [[market share]] to [[Steam (software)|Steam]] as a result.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/126427/Interview_Jonathan_Blow__Xbox_Live_Arcade_A_Pain_In_The_Ass_For_Indies.php|title=Interview: Jonathan Blow \u2013 Xbox Live Arcade 'A Pain In The Ass' For Indies|website=Gamasutra|date=2011-08-11|accessdate=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Jonathan Blow}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TH9VCN6UkyQ&list=PLmV5I2fxaiCKfxMBrNsU1kgKJXD3PkyxO A Programming Language For Games]\n*[http://www.gamasutra.com/php-bin/news_index.php?story=19748/ Gamasutra interview with Jonathan Blow]\n\n{{Indie Game: The Movie}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blow, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:Video game writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:American computer programmers]]\n[[Category:American video game designers]]\n[[Category:American video game programmers]]\n", "name_user": "Ivan.braidi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:early life infos as himself said here: https://www.twitch.tv/videos/592307953?t=22m52s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jonathan_Blow"}
