n Slovenia|Football]]\n\n{{Slovenia-footy-competition-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Frietjes", "label": "safe", "comment": "expand templates perFb team TfD outcomeandFb competition TfD outcomeandFb cl TfD outcomeandFb rbr TfD outcome", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1970%E2%80%9371_Slovenian_Republic_League"}
{"title_page": "Schooner", "text_new": "{{short description|Sailing vessel}}\n{{other uses|Schooner (disambiguation)}}\n[[Image:Lewis R. French NHL.jpg|thumb|[[Lewis R. French (schooner)|''Lewis R. French'']], a gaff-rigged topsail schooner]]\nA '''schooner''' is a type of [[sailing ship]], as defined by its rig configuration. Typically it has two<ref name=\"asa\">{{cite web |title=What\u2019s in a Rig \u2013 The Schooner |url=https://asa.com/news/2015/12/09/whats-in-a-rig-the-schooner/ |website=American Sailing Association |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> or more [[mast (sailing)|mast]]s, the [[foremast]] being slightly shorter than the [[mainmast]].<ref>{{cite web |title=schooner |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/schooner |website=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref> \n\nPronounced {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|k|u\u02d0|n|\u0259r}}, the term first appeared in eastern North America in the early 1700s.<ref>{{cite web |title=schooner |url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/schooner |website=Dictionary.com |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> The name may be related to a [[Scots language]] word meaning to skip over water,<ref name=britannica/> or to skip stones.<ref>{{cite web |title=schooner |url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/schooner |website=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe schooner is an evolution of the [[fore-and-aft rig]].  a rig consisting mainly of [[sails]] set along the line of the [[keel]] rather than perpendicular to it.<ref>{{Cite book   | last = Knight   | first = Austin Melvin   | authorlink =    | coauthors =    | title = Modern seamanship   | publisher = D. Van Nostrand   | year = 1910   | location = New York   | pages = 507\u2013532   | url =    | doi =    | id =    | isbn = }}</ref> This rig had itself been developed from earlier rigs such as the [[lateen]].{{Citation needed|reason=Gaff rig is believed to be derived from the spritsail, not lateen. See, for example, John Leather's definitive book on gaff rig.|date=April 2020}} It is not known when the rig we now call a schooner appeared. The earliest known illustration of a schooner depicts a yacht owned by the burgomasters of Amsterdam, drawn by the Dutch artist Rool and dated 1600. Later examples show schooners in Amsterdam in 1638 and [[New Amsterdam]] in 1627. Paintings by [[Willem van de Velde the Younger|Van de Velde]] (1633-1707) and an engraving by [[Jan Kip]] of the Thames at Lambeth, dated 1697, suggest that schooner rig was common in England and Holland by the end of the 18th century. The ''Royal Transport'' was an example of a large British-built schooner, launched in 1695 at Chatham.<ref name=\"Leather 1970\">{{cite book |last1=Leather |first1=John |title=Gaff Rig |date=1970 |publisher=Adlard Coles Limited |location=London |isbn=0 229 97489 9}}</ref><ref name=\"MacGregor\">{{cite book |last1=MacGregor |first1=David R. |title=Schooners in Four Centuries |date=1982 |publisher=Argus Books Ltd. |location=Hemel Hempstead |isbn=0 85242 774 3}}</ref><ref name=Marquardt>{{cite book |last1=Marquardt |first1=Karl Heinz |title=The global schooner : origins, development, design and construction 1695-1845 |date=2013 |publisher=Conway Maritime |isbn=9780851779300 |pages=7-13 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?redir_esc=y&id=SxRUAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe type was further developed in [[British North America]] starting around 1713.<ref name=britannica>{{cite web |last1=Wallenfeldt |first1=Jeff |title=Schooner |url=https://www.britannica.com/technology/schooner |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> In the 1700s and 1800s in what is now [[New England]] and [[Atlantic Canada]] schooners became popular for coastal trade, requiring a smaller crew for their size compared to then traditional ocean crossing [[square rig]] ships,<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Schooner |short=x}}</ref> and being fast and versatile.<ref name=\"asa\" /> Three-masted schooners were introduced around 1800.<ref name=\"Marquardt\" />\n\nSchooners were popular on both sides of the Atlantic in the late 1800s and early 1900s. By 1910, 45 five-masted and 10 six-masted schooners had been built in [[Bath, Maine]] and other [[Penobscot Bay]] towns. The [[Thomas W. Lawson (ship)|''Thomas W. Lawson'']] was the only seven-masted schooner built.\n\nAlthough highly popular in their time, schooners were replaced by more efficient [[sloops]], [[yawl]]s and [[ketch]]es<ref name=\"asa\"/> as sailboats, and in the freight business they were replaced by [[steamship]]s, barges, and railroads.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Great Coal Schooners |url=https://penobscotmarinemuseum.org/pbho-1/ships-shipbuilding/great-coal-schooners |website=Penobscot Marine Museum |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Rig types==\nVarious types of schooners are defined by their rig configuration. Most have a [[bowsprit]] although some were built without one for crew safety, such as ''[[Adventure (schooner)|Adventure]]''.\n\nThe following varieties were built:\n[[File:The Petitcodiac River at High Water.jpg|thumb|Tern schooner at dockside {{circa|1910}}. This design is notable for all three masts being of equal height.]]\n* [[Grand Banks]] fishing schooner: similar to ''[[Bluenose]]'', includes a gaff [[topsail]] on the main mast and a [[staysail]]. In the winter this would sail as a two-masted fishing schooner, without and [[topmast]]s and their upper sails.<ref name=\"nsm\">{{cite web |title=Sailing Ship Rigs |url=https://maritimemuseum.novascotia.ca/research/sailing-ship-rigs |website=Maritime Museum of the Atlantic |publisher=Nova Scotia Museum |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> Surviving gaff-rigged two-masters include ''[[Effie M. Morrissey]]'', [[Grace Bailey (schooner)|''Grace Bailey'']], ''[[Roseway]]'', and [[Western Union (schooner)|''Western Union'']].\n* Square topsail schooner: includes square topsails.<ref name=\"nsm\"/> A version with raked masts and known for its great speed, called the [[Baltimore Clipper]] was popular in the early 1800s.\n* Four masted schooner: this design spread the sail area over many smaller sails, at a time when sails were hoisted by hand. These were used for coastal trade on the Atlantic coast of North America, the West Indies, South America, and some trans-Atlantic voyages.<ref name=\"nsm\"/>\n* Tern schooner: a three masted schooner very popular between 1880 and 1920.<ref name=\"nsm\"/> [[Wawona (schooner)|''Wawona'']], the largest ever built, sailed on the [[West_Coast_of_the_United_States|West Coast]] from 1897 to 1947.\n\n==Uses==\nSchooners were built primarily for cargo, passengers, and fishing. \n\nThe Norwegian polar schooner ''[[Fram]]'' was used by both [[Fridtjof Nansen]] and [[Roald Amundsen]] in their explorations of the poles.\n\n''Bluenose'' was both a successful fishing boat and a racer. [[America (yacht)|''America'']], eponym of [[America's Cup]], was one of the few schooners ever designed for racing. This race was long dominated by schooners. Three-masted schooner [[Atlantic (yacht)|''Atlantic'']] set the [[transatlantic sailing record]] for a [[monohull]] in the 1905 [[Kaiser's Cup]] race. The record remained unbroken for nearly 100 years.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/02/sports/othersports/schooner-breaks-centuryold-record-for-crossing-the.html| title= YACHT RACING; Schooner Breaks Century-Old Record for Crossing the Atlantic  | newspaper= New York Times | first=Nancy | last=Ramsey | date=2005-06-02 | accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Bluenose vs. Gertrude L. Thebaud, Wallace R. MacAskill, 26 October, 1938.webm|''[[Bluenose]]'' (winner) vs. ''[[Gertrude L. Thebaud]]'', International Fishermen's Trophy, 1938, final race\nFile:Aland post 1988 Schooner-Ingrid.jpg|[[\u00c5land]] 1988 schooner ''Ingrid''\nFile:Faroe stamp 196 schooner sanna.jpg|[[Faroe Islands]] stamp of schooner ''Sanna''\nThe scow schooner Caroline Dixon with a load of wood for the match factory.jpg|The schooner ''Caroline Dixon'' in the [[Oakland Estuary]], 1904\nFile:Sail plan schooner.svg|Two-masted sail plan\nFile:Double-topsail schooner (jackass brig).png|Double-topsail sail plan\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of schooners]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.nsschooner.ca/ Nova Scotia Schooner Association]\n\n{{Sailing Vessels and Rigs}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Schooners|*]]\n[[Category:Ship types]]\n[[Category:Sailing rigs and rigging]]\n[[Category:Dutch inventions]]\n[[Category:Ship designs of the Dutch Republic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sailing vessel}}\n{{other uses|Schooner (disambiguation)}}\n[[Image:Lewis R. French NHL.jpg|thumb|[[Lewis R. French (schooner)|''Lewis R. French'']], a gaff-rigged topsail schooner]]\nA '''schooner''' is a type of [[sailing ship]], as defined by its rig configuration. Typically it has two<ref name=\"asa\">{{cite web |title=What\u2019s in a Rig \u2013 The Schooner |url=https://asa.com/news/2015/12/09/whats-in-a-rig-the-schooner/ |website=American Sailing Association |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> or more [[mast (sailing)|mast]]s, the [[foremast]] being slightly shorter than the [[mainmast]].<ref>{{cite web |title=schooner |url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/schooner |website=Merriam-Webster |accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref> \n\nPronounced {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|k|u\u02d0|n|\u0259r}}, the term first appeared in eastern North America in the early 1700s.<ref>{{cite web |title=schooner |url=https://www.dictionary.com/browse/schooner |website=Dictionary.com |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> The name may be related to a [[Scots language]] word meaning to skip over water,<ref name=britannica/> or to skip stones.<ref>{{cite web |title=schooner |url=https://www.etymonline.com/word/schooner |website=Online Etymology Dictionary |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe schooner is an evolution of the [[fore-and-aft rig]].  a rig consisting mainly of [[sails]] set along the line of the [[keel]] rather than perpendicular to it.<ref>{{Cite book   | last = Knight   | first = Austin Melvin   | authorlink =    | coauthors =    | title = Modern seamanship   | publisher = D. Van Nostrand   | year = 1910   | location = New York   | pages = 507\u2013532   | url =    | doi =    | id =    | isbn = }}</ref> This rig had itself been developed from earlier rigs such as the [[lateen]].{{Citation needed|reason=Gaff rig is believed to be derived from the spritsail, not lateen. See, for example, John Leather's definitive book on gaff rig.|date=April 2020}} It is not known when the rig we now call a schooner appeared. The earliest known illustration of a schooner depicts a yacht owned by the burgomasters of Amsterdam, drawn by the Dutch artist Rool and dated 1600. Later examples show schooners in Amsterdam in 1638 and [[New Amsterdam]] in 1627. Paintings by [[Willem van de Velde the Younger|Van de Velde]] (1633-1707) and an engraving by [[Jan Kip]] of the Thames at Lambeth, dated 1697, suggest that schooner rig was common in England and Holland by the end of the 18th century. The ''Royal Transport'' was an example of a large British-built schooner, launched in 1695 at Chatham.<ref name=\"Leather 1970\">{{cite book |last1=Leather |first1=John |title=Gaff Rig |date=1970 |publisher=Adlard Coles Limited |location=London |isbn=0 229 97489 9}}</ref><ref name=\"MacGregor\">{{cite book |last1=MacGregor |first1=David R. |title=Schooners in Four Centuries |date=1982 |publisher=Argus Books Ltd. |location=Hemel Hempstead |isbn=0 85242 774 3}}</ref>\n\nThe type was further developed in [[British North America]] starting around 1713.<ref name=britannica>{{cite web |last1=Wallenfeldt |first1=Jeff |title=Schooner |url=https://www.britannica.com/technology/schooner |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> In the 1700s and 1800s in what is now [[New England]] and [[Atlantic Canada]] schooners became popular for coastal trade, requiring a smaller crew for their size compared to then traditional ocean crossing [[square rig]] ships,<ref>{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Schooner |short=x}}</ref> and being fast and versatile.<ref name=\"asa\" /> Three-masted schooners were introduced around 1800.<ref name=\"Marquardt\" />\n\nSchooners were popular on both sides of the Atlantic in the late 1800s and early 1900s. By 1910, 45 five-masted and 10 six-masted schooners had been built in [[Bath, Maine]] and other [[Penobscot Bay]] towns. The [[Thomas W. Lawson (ship)|''Thomas W. Lawson'']] was the only seven-masted schooner built.\n\nAlthough highly popular in their time, schooners were replaced by more efficient [[sloops]], [[yawl]]s and [[ketch]]es<ref name=\"asa\"/> as sailboats, and in the freight business they were replaced by [[steamship]]s, barges, and railroads.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Great Coal Schooners |url=https://penobscotmarinemuseum.org/pbho-1/ships-shipbuilding/great-coal-schooners |website=Penobscot Marine Museum |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Rig types==\nVarious types of schooners are defined by their rig configuration. Most have a [[bowsprit]] although some were built without one for crew safety, such as ''[[Adventure (schooner)|Adventure]]''.\n\nThe following varieties were built:\n[[File:The Petitcodiac River at High Water.jpg|thumb|Tern schooner at dockside {{circa|1910}}. This design is notable for all three masts being of equal height.]]\n* [[Grand Banks]] fishing schooner: similar to ''[[Bluenose]]'', includes a gaff [[topsail]] on the main mast and a [[staysail]]. In the winter this would sail as a two-masted fishing schooner, without and [[topmast]]s and their upper sails.<ref name=\"nsm\">{{cite web |title=Sailing Ship Rigs |url=https://maritimemuseum.novascotia.ca/research/sailing-ship-rigs |website=Maritime Museum of the Atlantic |publisher=Nova Scotia Museum |accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref> Surviving gaff-rigged two-masters include ''[[Effie M. Morrissey]]'', [[Grace Bailey (schooner)|''Grace Bailey'']], ''[[Roseway]]'', and [[Western Union (schooner)|''Western Union'']].\n* Square topsail schooner: includes square topsails.<ref name=\"nsm\"/> A version with raked masts and known for its great speed, called the [[Baltimore Clipper]] was popular in the early 1800s.\n* Four masted schooner: this design spread the sail area over many smaller sails, at a time when sails were hoisted by hand. These were used for coastal trade on the Atlantic coast of North America, the West Indies, South America, and some trans-Atlantic voyages.<ref name=\"nsm\"/>\n* Tern schooner: a three masted schooner very popular between 1880 and 1920.<ref name=\"nsm\"/> [[Wawona (schooner)|''Wawona'']], the largest ever built, sailed on the [[West_Coast_of_the_United_States|West Coast]] from 1897 to 1947.\n\n==Uses==\nSchooners were built primarily for cargo, passengers, and fishing. \n\nThe Norwegian polar schooner ''[[Fram]]'' was used by both [[Fridtjof Nansen]] and [[Roald Amundsen]] in their explorations of the poles.\n\n''Bluenose'' was both a successful fishing boat and a racer. [[America (yacht)|''America'']], eponym of [[America's Cup]], was one of the few schooners ever designed for racing. This race was long dominated by schooners. Three-masted schooner [[Atlantic (yacht)|''Atlantic'']] set the [[transatlantic sailing record]] for a [[monohull]] in the 1905 [[Kaiser's Cup]] race. The record remained unbroken for nearly 100 years.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/02/sports/othersports/schooner-breaks-centuryold-record-for-crossing-the.html| title= YACHT RACING; Schooner Breaks Century-Old Record for Crossing the Atlantic  | newspaper= New York Times | first=Nancy | last=Ramsey | date=2005-06-02 | accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Bluenose vs. Gertrude L. Thebaud, Wallace R. MacAskill, 26 October, 1938.webm|''[[Bluenose]]'' (winner) vs. ''[[Gertrude L. Thebaud]]'', International Fishermen's Trophy, 1938, final race\nFile:Aland post 1988 Schooner-Ingrid.jpg|[[\u00c5land]] 1988 schooner ''Ingrid''\nFile:Faroe stamp 196 schooner sanna.jpg|[[Faroe Islands]] stamp of schooner ''Sanna''\nThe scow schooner Caroline Dixon with a load of wood for the match factory.jpg|The schooner ''Caroline Dixon'' in the [[Oakland Estuary]], 1904\nFile:Sail plan schooner.svg|Two-masted sail plan\nFile:Double-topsail schooner (jackass brig).png|Double-topsail sail plan\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of schooners]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.nsschooner.ca/ Nova Scotia Schooner Association]\n\n{{Sailing Vessels and Rigs}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Schooners|*]]\n[[Category:Ship types]]\n[[Category:Sailing rigs and rigging]]\n[[Category:Dutch inventions]]\n[[Category:Ship designs of the Dutch Republic]]\n", "name_user": "ThoughtIdRetired", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:reinstate accidentally removed ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schooner"}
{"title_page": "Honda Sport ATCs", "text_new": "Sport ATC's, produced until 1987, were build specifically for performance in mind, designed for use in racing, or for aggressive trail riding. The machines lack luggage racks and other utilitarian features, common place on most other ATC's or ATV's.\n\nIn 1970, [[Honda]]\u2019 created the three-wheeled \u201cAll Terrain Cycle\u201d market nearly single-handedly with the release of the [[Honda US90]] <ref>{{cite web|author=Atc90.tripod.com |url= http://atc90.tripod.com/hondaatc90/id17.html |title=ATC90-History |website=atc90.tripod.com| |accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>. As the popularity of ATC's exploded in the late seventies, Honda began to diversify their line. Originally catering to winter activity, campers, hunters and weekend Recreational riders that ATC's were envisioned for, their research showed there was a market for both utility-focused machines, for growing commercial and agricultural use, and creating dedicated sport models intended for leisure and competition use.\n\nThis led to the creation of the [[Honda ATC250R|ATC250R]] <ref>{{cite web|author=Berts Mega Mall |url= https://www.bertsmegamall.com/--what-happened-to-the-honda-atc |title=What Happened to Honda ATC\u2019s |website=Bertsmegamall.com|date=2007-08-24 |accessdate=2020-04-12 |url-status=live}}</ref>, a 2-stroke racing ATC based on the [[Honda CR250R|CR250]] motocross line in 1981. Honda would further produce 3 more Sport ATC's, using 4-stroke engines <ref>{{cite web|url= https://hondanews.com/en-US/powersports/releases/release-5b1200e2933243e8b0255b2ef55d396d-honda-atv-model-history-timeline-1970-present-1 |title=Honda model history time line |website=hondanews.com|date=2011-07-11 |accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>. While the ATC250R remains a popular model for collectors, due to its high-performance 2-stroke engines and racing heritage, the 4-stroke \u201cX\u201d ATC's continue to be popular trail machines.\n\n{{Main|List of Honda Three-wheeled all-terrain vehicles}}\n\n==Honda ATC200X==\n\n{{Infobox Motorcycle\n|name             = Honda ATC200X\n|manufacturer     = [[Honda]]\n|parent_company   = \n|production       = 1983 - 1987\n|assembly         =\n|predecessor      = \n|successor        = \n|class            = Sport ATC\n|engine           = {{Convert|192|cc|abbr=on}} [[Radiator (engine cooling)|Air-cooled]] [[four-stroke]] [[Single-cylinder engine|single]]\n|bore_stroke      = 65 x 57.8mm \n|compression Ratio      = 9.6:1\n|compression      = 142 - 170psi\n|top_speed        = <45Mph \n|power            = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|torque           = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|ignition         = CDI \n|transmission     = 5-speed with Auto-Clutch \n|frame            = steel  \n|suspension       =\n|front brake      = Hydraulic Disc Brake \n|rear brake       = Hydraulic Disc Brake\n|front tires            = 23.5 x 8 x 11\n|rear tires       = 22 x 8 x 11\n|wheelbase        = 46.5 in. \n|length           = 72.4 in. \n|width            = 42.5\n|height           = \n|seat_height      = 27.6 in. \n|dry_weight       = 282.1 lbs.\n|wet_weight       = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|fuel_capacity    = \n|oil_capacity     = \n|fuel_consumption = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|turning_radius   = \n|related          = \n|sp               =\n|footnotes        = Information provided via Honda ATC200X Service Manual \n}}\n\nThe ATC200X was Hondas first 4-stroke Sport model released, in 1983. The machine was based on the [[Honda ATC200|ATC200]] line, but was virtually unique in its set-up and engine tuning. It featured a 5-speed transmission with manual clutch, and full suspension with 7.3\u201d of front travel and 6.7\u201d of rear travel. <ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oscarmayer.net/atc/manuals/honda/atc200x_83-85_servicemanual.pdf |accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Honda ATC250SX==\n\n{{Infobox Motorcycle\n|name             = Honda ATC250SX\n|manufacturer     = [[Honda]]\n|parent_company   = \n|production       = 1985 - 1987\n|assembly         =\n|predecessor      = \n|successor        = \n|class            = Sport ATC\n|engine           = {{Convert|246|cc|abbr=on}} [[Radiator (engine cooling)|Air-cooled]] [[four-stroke]] [[Single-cylinder engine|single]]\n|bore_stroke      = 66 x 72mm \n|compression Ratio      = 8.0:1\n|compression      = 142 - 170psi\n|top_speed        = < 50 Mph \n|power            = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|torque           = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|ignition         = CDI \n|transmission     = 5-speed w/Reverse and Auto Clutch\n|frame            = steel  \n|suspension       =\n|front brake      = Drum Brake \n|rear brake       = Drum Brake\n|front tires            = 22 x 11 x 8\n|rear tires       = 22 x 11 x 8\n|wheelbase        = 48.6in. \n|length           = 74.2 in. \n|width            =\n|height           = \n|seat_height      = 27.8 in. \n|dry_weight       = 357 lbs.\n|wet_weight       = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|fuel_capacity    = \n|oil_capacity     = \n|fuel_consumption = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|turning_radius   = \n|related          = \n|sp               =  \n| footnotes        = Information provided via 1985 Honda Service Manual\n}}\n\nThe ATC250SX was introduced alongside the ATC350X in 1985, and available for three model years. Decidedly more a trail machine than a racer, this ATC is equipped with a 246cc 4-Stroke Air-cooled OHV engine, with 5-speed auto-clutch transmission and Shaft final drive. Stoppage was handled by front and rear drum brakes, and it featured a reverse gear, unique among Honda Sport ATC's. This added to the weight, of nearly 50lbs more than similar machines. <ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oscarmayer.net/atc/manuals/honda/atc250sx_85-87_servicemanual.pdf |title=Honda ATC250SX Factory Service Manual |accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Honda ATC350X==\n\n{{Infobox Motorcycle\n|name             = Honda ATC350X\n|manufacturer     = [[Honda]]\n|parent_company   = \n|production       = 1985 - 1987\n|assembly         =\n|predecessor      = \n|successor        = \n|class            = Sport ATC\n|engine           = {{Convert|350|cc|abbr=on}} [[Radiator (engine cooling)|Air-cooled]] [[four-stroke]] [[Single-cylinder engine|single]]\n|bore_stroke      = 81 x 68mm \n|compression Ratio      = 8.5:1\n|compression      = 150- 178psi\n|top_speed        = < 60 Mph \n|power            = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|torque           = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|ignition         = CDI \n|transmission     = 6-speed with Manual Clutch\n|frame            = steel  \n|suspension       =\n|front brake      = Hydraulic Disc Brake \n|rear brake       = Hydraulic Disc Brake\n|front tires            = 23.5 x 11 x 8\n|rear tires       = 22 x 10 x 9\n|wheelbase        = 48.6in. \n|length           = 74.4 in. \n|width            = 43.9\n|height           = \n|seat_height      = 27.8 in. \n|dry_weight       = 320 lbs.\n|wet_weight       = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|fuel_capacity    = \n|oil_capacity     = \n|fuel_consumption = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|turning_radius   = \n|related          = \n|footnotes        = Information provided via Honda ATC350X Service manual\n|sp               =  \n}}\n\nHonda's largest displacement ATC, the ATC350X, would be produced for two years in the United States. Equipped with a 350cc 4-Stroke Air-cooled OHV engine and 6-speed Manual Clutch transmission to a Chain final drive, the focus was purely on performance. <ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oscarmayer.net/atc/manuals/honda/85-86_ATC350X_Parts_Fiche.pdf |accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Honda ATC250R==\n\n{{Main|Honda ATC250R}}\n\nThe ATC250R, built for track racing, was produced from 1981\u20131987. Originally equipped with a 248cc Air-cooled engine and 5-speed transmission, it received a 246cc 2-Stroke Liquid cooled engine and 6-speed transmission in its third, and last, iteration.\n\n==References==\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "Sport ATC's, produced until 1987, were build specifically for performance in mind, designed for use in racing, or for aggressive trail riding. The machines lack luggage racks and other utilitarian features, common place on most other ATC's or ATV's.\n\nIn 1970, [[Honda]]\u2019 created the three-wheeled \u201cAll Terrain Cycle\u201d market nearly single-handedly with the release of the [[Honda US90]] <ref>{{cite web|author=Atc90.tripod.com |url= http://atc90.tripod.com/hondaatc90/id17.html |title=ATC90-History |website=atc90.tripod.com| |accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>. As the popularity of ATC's exploded in the late seventies, Honda began to diversify their line. Originally catering to winter activity, campers, hunters and weekend Recreational riders that ATC's were envisioned for, their research showed there was a market for both utility-focused machines, for growing commercial and agricultural use, and creating dedicated sport models intended for leisure and competition use.\n\nThis led to the creation of the [[Honda ATC250R|ATC250R]] <ref>{{cite web|author=Berts Mega Mall |url= https://www.bertsmegamall.com/--what-happened-to-the-honda-atc |title=What Happened to Honda ATC\u2019s |website=Bertsmegamall.com|date=2007-08-24 |accessdate=2020-04-12 |url-status=live}}</ref>, a 2-stroke racing ATC based on the [[Honda CR250R|CR250]] motocross line in 1981. Honda would further produce 3 more Sport ATC's, using 4-stroke engines <ref>{{cite web|url= https://hondanews.com/en-US/powersports/releases/release-5b1200e2933243e8b0255b2ef55d396d-honda-atv-model-history-timeline-1970-present-1 |title=Honda model history time line |website=hondanews.com|date=2011-07-11 |accessdate=2020-04-15 |url-status=live}}</ref>. While the ATC250R remains a popular model for collectors, due to its high-performance 2-stroke engines and racing heritage, the 4-stroke \u201cX\u201d ATC's continue to be popular trail machines.\n\n{{Main|List of Honda Three-wheeled all-terrain vehicles}}\n\n==Honda ATC200X==\n\n{{Infobox Motorcycle\n|name             = Honda ATC200X\n|manufacturer     = [[Honda]]\n|parent_company   = \n|production       = 1983 - 1987\n|assembly         =\n|predecessor      = \n|successor        = \n|class            = Sport ATC\n|engine           = {{Convert|192|cc|abbr=on}} [[Radiator (engine cooling)|Air-cooled]] [[four-stroke]] [[Single-cylinder engine|single]]\n|bore_stroke      = 65 x 57.8mm \n|compression Ratio      = 9.6:1\n|compression      = 142 - 170psi\n|top_speed        = <45Mph \n|power            = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|torque           = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|ignition         = CDI \n|transmission     = 5-speed with Auto-Clutch \n|frame            = steel  \n|suspension       =\n|front brake      = Hydraulic Disc Brake \n|rear brake       = Hydraulic Disc Brake\n|front tires            = 23.5 x 8 x 11\n|rear tires       = 22 x 8 x 11\n|wheelbase        = 46.5 in. \n|length           = 72.4 in. \n|width            = 42.5\n|height           = \n|seat_height      = 27.6 in. \n|dry_weight       = 282.1 lbs.\n|wet_weight       = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|fuel_capacity    = \n|oil_capacity     = \n|fuel_consumption = <!-- Please cite a 3rd party source! -->\n|turning_radius   = \n|related          = \n|sp               =\n|footnotes        = Information provided via Honda ATC200X Service Manual \n}}\n\nThe ATC200X was Hondas first 4-stroke Sport model released, in 1983. The machine was based on the [[Honda ATC200|ATC200]] line, but was virtually unique in its set-up and engine tuning. It featured a 5-speed transmission with manual clutch, and full suspension with 7.3\u201d of front travel and 6.7\u201d of rear travel. <ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.oscarmayer.net/atc/man